<TEXT>
a un delegation arrived in tehran 
sunday to begin the first outside investigation into alleged human 
rights abuses since the 1979 islamic revolution 
the delegations trip marks a significant breakthrough for human 
rights campaigners who have long accused iran of abuses thousands 
of people reportedly have been executed since 1979 
irans official islamic republic news agency monitored in 
nicosia said the un team was scheduled to meet several senior 
iranian officials but did not identify them 
the mission is led by reynaldo galindo pohl the un human 
rights commissions special envoy and an international law expert 
from el salvador 
the un investigation comes amid efforts by president hashemi 
rafsanjani leader of irans socalled pragmatists to liberalize 
society after a decade of rigid moslem fundamentalism 
rafsanjani was elected july 28 he since has dumped prominent 
radicals from senior government posts as part of his effort to 
renew ties with the west and attract badly needed foreign 
investment to revitalize irans moribund economy 
shortly after the un team arrived tehran radio reported that 
the chief of irans judiciary ayatollah mohammad yazdi told a 
meeting of prison directors in tehran that all inmates must be 
treated with respect and in accordance to islamic law 
it is not known how many people are behind bars in iran 
dissident groups claim thousands of political prisoners are held 
without trial languishing in appalling conditions and subjected to 
torture 
tehran invited galindo pohl to visit iran in november ending a 
longtime policy of barring foreign observers from checking its 
human rights practices 
the invitation was extended after galindo pohl produced an 
interim report based mainly on evidence from iranian dissidents 
that abuses continued after irans revolutionary leader ayatollah 
ruhollah khomeini died june 3 
that report cited 1700 people possibly executed and said 
prisoners were flogged whipped on the soles of their feet with 
barbed wire burned with cigarettes sexually abused locked up in 
heated boxes and subjected to mock executions 
amnesty international the londonbased human rights 
organization said in its 1989 report that iran executed more than 
1200 political prisoners between july 1988 and december 1988 
the english language tehran times daily which usually reflects 
rafsanjanis thinking said jan 17 that the un missions visit 
was the best way to neutralize baseless propaganda by the western 
media and enemies of the islamic revolution 
galindo pohl will submit a report on his findings to the human 
rights commissions annual sixweek session in geneva that is to 
begin jan 29 
nearly 1000 people reportedly have been executed since december 
1988 iran responded to criticism of those executions by saying 
that nearly all involved drug traffickers convicted by islamic 
courts iranian opposition groups said many were political 
prisoners however 
</TEXT>
