<TEXT>
the air traffic controller who was in charge of 
two planes involved in a fatal runway crash last week was stripped 
of his certification a federal investigator said sunday 
the controller failed to warn the pilot of an eastern airlines 
boeing 727 that had just landed that there was a smaller plane on 
the runway in front of him said the official from the national 
transportation safety board 
the pilot of the smaller plane a twinengine beechcraft king 
air was killed in the accident thursday night at hartsfield 
atlanta international airport the copilot of the beechcraft was 
slightly injured but nobody aboard the airliner was hurt 
the pilot of the eastern plane which carried 141 passengers 
spotted the smaller plane too late and tried to veer away but the 
airliners right wing struck the smaller planes cockpit 
safety board investigators were told the faa had decertified the 
controller due to an error made because procedures were not 
followed the ntsb said in a news release sunday under the name of 
chief investigator bob macintosh 
macintosh refused to answer questions 
the controller whose name was withheld may apply for 
retraining and recertification but wont be allowed to direct air 
traffic without certification 
the controller was hired by the faa in 1982 and has worked in 
the atlanta tower since october 1988 the ntsb said he took his 
post about four minutes before the accident 
ntsb investigators said saturday the pilot of eastern flight 111 
from new york wasnt warned of the smaller plane on the runway 
ahead of him as is required 
during a 2hour interview with ntsb investigators sunday the 
controller acknowledged it was his responsibility to ensure the 
runway was clear before allowing another plane to land the ntsb 
statement said 
he stated that he thought that the king air had cleared the 
runway and was surprised that it had not the statement said 
however he did not actually observe the king air clear the 
runway he could not explain why he did not offer traffic 
information to eastern 111 about the king air flight as required by 
air traffic control procedures 
the controller also indicated that he was distracted by two 
other aircraft one that had just landed and another on landing 
approach that had reported a possible hydraulic problem the 
statement said 
the eastern pilot 23year veteran ralph orlando blamed the 
crash on the controller 
we should have been advised at a minimum that there was a 
small plane and that it might not be cleared orlando said 
apparently no one in the tower saw the collision macintosh said 
the pilot who was killed eric thomas 30 worked for 
atlantabased epps air service 
</TEXT>
