<TEXT>
investigators are concluding the bush 
administration exaggerated ousted panamanian dictator manuel 
antonio noriegas wealth the miami herald reported sunday 
many of the assets cited by the administration as evidence of 
noriegas fortune belonged to panamas defense forces or are 
registered to businessmen close to him according to documents 
emerging from panamanian government offices in the aftermath of the 
dec 20 us invasion 
a case in point the herald said was the us state department 
allegation that noriega owned a boeing 727 jet three lear jets and 
three luxury boats named macho i macho ii and macho iii 
documents found in recent weeks suggest that none of those 
planes and boats may be traceable to noreiga unidentified 
officials of the usinstalled panamanian government with access 
to the seized records told the newspaper 
that could complicate efforts by prosecutors to portray noriega 
as an immensely wealthy man in the former generals upcoming 
federsal trial on drug charges in miami 
noriega is accused of making millions in protection payments 
from colombian drug traffickers who used panama to fly drugs to the 
united states 
the boeing 727 purchased in 1983 for 22 million was first 
acquired by the staterun air panama airline and later transferred 
to panamas defense forces air traffic authorities said 
of the three executive jets a lear 35 that was regularly used 
by noriega was rented by panamas defense forces to a miami company 
for 230000 a month officials said a second lear jet appears to 
be partly owned by carlos duque a businessmanpoltician who made 
millions from his association with the former dictator officials 
said they dont know of a third lear jet used by noriega 
the macho i and macho ii were owned by carlos wittgreen another 
businessman who profited greatly from his friendship with noriega 
documents show no records on the third boat have been found 
noriega loyalists said the general used the military aircraft in 
his capacity as defense forces commander the boats were simply 
lent to him by his best friends they said 
all these properties cited by the us government exist but 
were not his said mario rognoni a former commerce minister with 
the noriega regime its like saying that camp david belongs to 
president bush 
officials of the new civilian government counter that there is 
widespread evidence that noriega amassed a significant fortune 
after taking over the defense forces in 1983 
but officials privately concede that the us government may 
have liberally mixed fact with fiction in its efforts to convince 
the world about noriegas crimes the herald said the state 
departments contention that noriegas personal wealth was at least 
200 to 300 million will be hard to prove investigators said 
</TEXT>
