<TEXT>
the late us supreme court justice abe fortas 
violated court confidentiality in 1966 by leaking information to 
president johnson a history professor said citing newly released 
fbi records 
the alleged leaks about court deliberations to the white house 
and the fbi involved information that might discredit robert f 
kennedy a former attorney general and political rival of johnson 
the documents released to marquette university history 
professor athan theoharis under the freedom of information act 
were outlined in the milwaukee journal on sunday 
fbi files say fortas who died in 1982 was cautioned by the 
agency he would violate judicial ethics by reporting on private 
discussions among the courts justices the paper said 
the records show fortas johnson and white house aides saw an 
opportunity to associate kennedy with an illegal eavesdropping 
incident that occurred while he was attorney general in 1963 the 
paper said fortas discussed the case with the white house 
it raises real questions about fortas role on the court and 
the degree with which he identified with the partisan interests and 
antikennedy forces in the johnson administration theoharis 
author of a 1988 book on fbi director j edgar hoover told the 
paper 
fortas resigned from the court in 1969 during an unrelated 
ethics matter hoover died in 1972 and johnson in 1973 
theoharis said the files show fortas violated the constitutions 
doctrine of separation of court and executive power by agreeing to 
provide inside information to fbi assistant director cd de loach 
he should have thrown de loach out on his ear theoharis 
said 
de loach now retired told the journal in a telephone interview 
from hilton head island sc that he could recall nothing of the 
case discussed in the files 
the case involved bugging of a hotel room occupied by fred 
black a washington dc lobbyist who was appealing a fraud 
conviction to the high court 
solicitor general thurgood marshall disclosed the the bugging 
a memo written by hoover june 14 1966 said fortas called 
marshall dumb marshall now sits on the supreme court 
the court suspended deliberations in the black case and asked 
attorney general nicholas katzenbach if the fbi bugging was 
authorized because kennedy was attorney general at the time of the 
bugging there appeared an opportunity to discredit him the 
newspaper said 
a memorandum by de loach quoted fortas as saying the entire 
matter boiled down to a continuing fight for the presidency 
fortas volunteered to talk on a confidential basis at any time 
it said 
the theoharis documents show fortas told de loach the justices 
held a confidential meeting among themselves and decided to 
review fbi records before ruling on the black appeal 
fortas suggested a plan to de loach to protect the president 
and the fbi by appointing a projohnson arbitrator to review fbi 
eavesdropping policy bypassing katzenbach the documents said 
fortas telephoned de loach june 21 to say johnson was appointing 
a threemember eavesdropping investigation panel johnson changed 
his mind two days later a de loach memo said 
the justice department said in july 1966 that hoover authorized 
the bugging under authority delegated by one or more of kennedys 
predecessors as attorney general 
in november the supreme court ordered a new trial for black 
calling the bugging illegal black was subsequently acquitted 
katzenbach interviewed by telephone in new jersey said the 
documents disclosures surprised him 
you think you know whats going on and you dont katzenbach 
said 
scott anderson a coauthor of the 1979 investigative book the 
brethen about the high court said the documents seem to show an 
unprecedented breach of supreme court tradition and procedure 
this screams impropriety said geoffrey miller a university 
of chicago law professor codes of ethics forbid judges from 
discussing judicial deliberations outside a courtroom he said 
its disgraceful said harvard law school professor charles 
fried 
</TEXT>
