<TEXT>
soviet soldiers waged fierce street battles with 
militants saturday in the southern republic of azerbaijan and at 
least 57 people were killed the government said witnesses said 
the death toll could be far higher 
the street is covered with blood vadim korsh an editor of 
azerbaijans official news agency azerinform said of the scene at 
a military garrison in the capital baku 
one activist said more than 100 local troops at the garrison 
joined the militants in fighting soviet soldiers thousands of 
which were sent to quell a week of ethnic and separatist violence 
it was the first report of rebellion in local ranks 
by evening residents were reporting that the sound of gunfire 
had stopped in the barracks and elsewhere in the city center 
early sunday moscow radio said soviet forces were in control of 
the city though some gunfire could still be heard the report 
quoted by the british broadcasting corp said the first night of a 
curfew passed in relative calm with 18 people arrested for 
violating the curfew 
azerbaijani president elmira kafarova on saturday denounced the 
gross violation of the republics sovereignty by the kremlins 
declaration of a state of emergency without the approval of local 
authorities 
the people of azerbaijan will never forgive anyone for the 
tragic way their sons and daughters have been killed she said 
in moscow president mikhail s gorbachev went on nationwide tv 
to appeal for an end to the violence that the government says has 
killed more than 129 people wounded 500 and chased thousands of 
armenians from their homes 
in the last two years the central authorities have sought to 
act in a patient and thoughtful manner trying to solve difficult 
problems exclusively by peaceful political means gorbachev said 
but militants had begun threatening to take over the government 
by force and are killing people he said 
this had to stop said gorbachev who also has had to deal 
with nationalist movements in other republics including 
neighboring georgia moldavia and the baltics 
in washington the bush administration called for restraint in 
the use of force and said the sending of troops to stop the 
violence should not become a cloak for the abridgment of the 
exercise of political rights 
iran which borders azerbaijan urged the soviet government to 
resolve the issue by employing peaceful means 
moscow sent troops to baku after fighting flared between the 
moslem azerbaijanis and mainly christian armenians the neighboring 
republics are locked in a decadesold dispute over the region of 
nagornokarabakh which is inside azerbaijan but populated mainly 
by armenians 
speakers at rallies in baku were reported to have demanded 
secession from the soviet union and unification with iran 
some 5000 regular army troops and thousands more interior 
ministry soldiers and police have moved in to try to restore order 
araz alizade of the opposition azerbaijani social democratic 
group said 120 azeribaijani soldiers under the command of a 
colonel spent the afternoon in a pitched battle with soviet troops 
in the salyanovsky barracks in downtown baku 
by evening the shooting stopped he said in a telephone 
interview from the city but he had no further details 
the official tass news agency quoted deputy defense ministry 
gen valentin varennikov as saying militants surrounded the 
barracks and that troops who moved in to defend it were attacked by 
snipers firing heavycaliber machine guns from rooftops 
the soldiers opened warning fire only in defense of strategic 
sites and their own lives if the attacks didnt stop they fired 
only on those who were threatening them he said 
the interior ministry reported 51 civilians and six soldiers 
dead saturday it said 287 civilians and 36 soldiers were wounded 
korsh said in a telephone interview from baku that corpses were 
strewn on the road to the citys airport 
it was impossible to independently verify government casualty 
figures as foreign reporters have been barred from the region 
azerbaijani activists claimed the number of dead climbed into 
the thousands after armored personnel carriers surrounded a central 
square in baku and opened fire with machine guns 
but arif yunosof of the azerbaijani social democratic group said 
the troops fired into the air in a vain attempt to dispel the crowd 
of 30000 to 40000 people 
troops moved into baku a caspian sea port of 18 million 
people early saturday army and internal security troops have been 
building up in armenia and azerbaijan for several days but they 
previously had not entered baku 
soldiers surrounded a square near the communist party 
headquarters where about 30000 azerbaijanis gathered in an 
antigovernment protest said leila unusova also of the 
azerbaijani social democrat group 
the biggest battles reportedly raged around the airport and 
military garrison where armed protesters had been trying to 
prevent troop reinforcements from traveling to the strifetorn 
areas 
the azerbaijan communist party chief abdulrakhman vezirov was 
fired and replaced by two people azerbaijan premier ayaz mutalibov 
and party second secretary viktor polyanichko tass reported 
censorship was in full force as part of the state of emergency 
tass had photographs of soldiers fighting civilians but editors 
said they were not permitted to release them 
radio moscow said the measure forbids strikes and street 
processions the use of duplicating equipment and the use of 
transport without special permission the first deputy foreign 
minister alexander bessmertnykh told reporters the measures and 
introduction of troops had improved the situation 
but the reports of mass rallies and the continued sound of 
gunshots ringing out in the capital indicated otherwise 
adding to the problems were daring political moves by 
azerbaijanis 
the legislature of the nakhichevan autonomous republic which is 
controlled by the republic voted to secede from azerbaijan as well 
as from the ussr news reports said 
nakhichevan is a small enclave of about 250000 people 
surrounded by armenia iran and turkey it has been under 
azerbaijans jurisdiction since 1924 violence broke out there jan 
1 when demonstrators forced open the border with iran in an effort 
to be reunited with their brethren in that country 
irans islamic republic news agency said the supreme soviet 
legislature in nakhichevan demanded soviet troops leave the enclave 
and appealed to turkey iran and the united nations for support 
