<TEXT>
lee patrick brown who takes office monday as 
new yorks 36th police commissioner has made a career of tackling 
troubled police departments 
nicknamed the iceman he is known as a cool deliberate 
some say stiff administrator who meticulously studies problems 
before acting 
his supporters say the 52yearold brown is a dedicated crime 
fighter prepared to tackle the nations largest city they call him 
a a thinking persons cop who recognizes the importance of fighting 
crime at its roots including trying to correct the social ills 
that foster criminals 
his detractors say he is more a politician than a policeman 
garnering good publicity for the department while the police force 
unravels from within 
when brown became public safety commissioner in atlanta in 1978 
the department was reeling from a series of child murders that 
shocked the nation antidiscrimination lawsuits and a promotion 
examinations scandal in 1982 he was appointed police chief in 
houston a city where the police had a triggerhappy reputation 
by the time he left both cities both police departments had won 
praise and many officials begged him to stay two recent incidents 
in houston in which white or hispanic officers have shot and killed 
black motorists have once again tarnished the departments image 
but brown emerged relatively unscathed just before he left 
houston he fired the officers involved 
his resume is impressive with a phd in criminology and a 
masters degree in sociology hes been a patrolman in san jose 
calif and a professor at portland state and howard universities 
browns past is not without controversy however and he has 
received a cold shoulder from new york police as he prepares to 
take over the nations largest police department 
