<TEXT>
stung by the loss of two top house democrats 
and the problems of five senators embroiled in a savings and loan 
furor congressional leaders are weighing a substantial revamping 
of campaign finance laws 
a bipartisan house task force is at work on the problem and 
senate leaders seem determined to watch what the house does before 
acting on their own complicating prospects for passage is the fact 
that all 435 members of the house and a third of the senate are up 
for reelection this year 
still speaker thomas s foley was able on sunday to predict 
passage of a reform bill in the house 
i think its going to happen in this session at least in 
the house the washington democrat said on nbcs meet the 
press 
congress historically has been reluctant to legislate in this 
politically touchy area especially in an election year and this 
issue has been bogged down in partisan argument since early 1988 
yet pressure is building thanks largely to the political 
brouhaha surrounding phoenix millionaire charles h keating jr and 
the five senators to whom he gave 13 million in campaign and 
other contributions in his fight with savings and loan regulators 
the five senators alan cranston dcalif dennis deconcini 
dariz john mccain rariz john glenn dohio and donald w 
riegle dmich are now subjects of senate ethics committee 
inquiries for interceding with sampl regulators on keatings behalf 
this political firestorm which ignited last year after house 
speaker jim wright and democratic whip tony coelho resigned amid 
ethics problems has given impetus to the fight for campaign 
finance reform 
with the exception of watergate i cant remember a single 
incident that has educated people all over the country on the real 
price that is paid in a campaign financing system that allows money 
to be used for buying influence said fred wertheimer head of 
the selfstyled citizens lobby common cause 
a 21member bipartisan house task force has been instructed by 
foley and republican leader robert h michel of illinois to have a 
bill ready as soon as possible after congress returns tuesday 
no specific date was set but congressional officials working on 
the package said the clear intent of foleys directions was to have 
a bipartisan package prepared for a vote in march 
in the senate democratic leader george mitchell of maine and 
gop leader bob dole of kansas discussed setting up a similar task 
force after congress adjourned last month 
while senate leaders want to see what the house does first 
before producing a package of their own the leader of the last 
failed reform effort sen david boren dokla is working with 
mccain one of the keating five on a bipartisan proposal 
wertheimers organization which advocates spending limits and 
federal financing of campaigns filed the initial complaint with 
the ethics panel last october this forced the inquiries into the 
five senators intervention with the federal home loan bank board 
on behalf of keatings nowcollapsed lincoln savings and loan 
based in irvine calif 
all five senators have denied they intervened with the bank 
board in the lincoln case because of keatings contributions the 
five said they often intercede with federal agencies on behalf of 
constituents who are not contributors 
just how much reform will be in a campaign finance bill that 
can win both democratic and republican support and not pose a 
serious threat to the careers of incumbent lawmakers is in doubt 
common cause has dropped its demand for public financing of the 
type used in presidential campaigns since the passage of the last 
significant campaign money law in 1974 following the watergate 
scandal 
public financing and voluntary spending ceilings wanted by 
democrats but opposed by republicans stymied the last reform 
effort in 198788 
after congress adjourned with the keating controversy fresh in 
its mind michel told the national press club he would give 
personal consideration to some type of cap indicating a 
softening in the gops historic opposition to spending ceilings 
instead of offering government campaign dollars to candidates 
who abide by voluntary spending ceilings compulsory caps are 
illegal under a supreme court decision democrats are talking of 
using discount mail and tv advertising rates as a carrot for 
compliance 
socalled soft money contributions which go to national and 
state party organizations or independent groups and foundations 
utilized by members of congress remain a major stumbling block 
most of those contributions do not now have to be reported to 
the federal election commission and only a few states such as 
california require their disclosure keating contributed 85000 
each to republican and democratic party committees in california 
where lincolns 29 thrift branches operated 
republican members of congress who rely on their party more 
than democrats for raising election money are opposed to any 
measure that would curb that ability but they want to restrict 
business trade association and labor pacs that increasingly are 
becoming the biggest source of cash for incumbent democrats 
theres always support for campaign finance reform in general 
but when it comes down to specifics thats where everything breaks 
down said ross baker a campaign finance expert at rutgers 
university 
until republicans get over their distaste for public financing 
and democrats give up their love affair with pacs he said the 
best reform would be requiring more disclosure 
the ultimate sanction against a candidate who takes too much 
money or money from the wrong people is that an opponent can 
use it as an issue he said thats the great dagger hanging 
over the heads of those five senators 
none of the keating five however is among the 33 senators 
up for reelection this year 
