<TEXT>
for the past 13 years robert randall has made 
regular trips to a pharmacy to get legally and free what many 
others buy on the street at the risk of arrest marijuana 
randall was the first person allowed by the federal government 
to use the drug for medical purposes in his case as a treatment 
for the blinding eye disease glaucoma under what is termed a 
compassionate protocol 
others have received permission to use marijuana legally for 
controlling nausea caused by anticancer drugs for pain relief and 
for controlling muscle spasms in people with multiple sclerosis 
but randall says its easier for patients to get the drug in an 
illegal street sale than through the legitimate but timeconsuming 
and bureaucratic process that allows governmentgrown marijuana to 
be distributed free by prescription as an experimental drug 
its an extraordinary process to engage in it stretches the 
word compassionate to the limit randall said an interview last 
week at his washington home ive watched one or two people go 
blind while waiting 
only four other people two with glaucoma one with cancer and 
one with aids currently are receiving marijuana from the 
government said randall president of the alliance for cannabis 
therapeutics 
the food and drug administration did not know how many people 
have gotten marijuana under a compassionate protocol but a 
spokesman said at least two dozen protocols some covering groups 
of patients have been approved since randalls in 1976 most of 
the protocols now are inactive either because patients have died 
or have switched to other drugs 
the process starts with a request from a physician for 
authorization to prescribe marijuana for a patient if the fda 
approves the physicians plans the request goes to the national 
institute for drug abuse which is responsible for growing the drug 
on a mississippi farm 
after nida certifies it has a supply of the drug the request 
goes to the drug enforcement administration which must assure 
tight control over distribution of the drug 
randalls group and the national organization for the reform of 
marijuana laws went to court again on friday to try to force the 
dea to change marijuanas status as a schedule i drug which is 
available only for research to a schedule ii drug which would 
make it available for patient use as morphine and cocaine are 
a dea administrative law judge in 1988 recommended that 
marijuana be reclassified but dea administrator john lawn rejected 
the recommendation dec 29 saying the judge ignored the scientific 
evidence 
randall said lawns action ignores the pain of the ill solely to 
promote his political agenda the war against illegal drugs 
for me marijuana is just another medication randall said 
adding that the only effect he gets from the drug is therapeutic 
it reduces the pressure inside his eye helping him retain his 
vision 
randall who turns 42 on tuesday gets by prescription 300 
neatly rolled marijuana cigarettes a month and smokes 10 of them 
each day he said he hasnt gotten high from the drug for years 
partly because of the low potency of governmentgrade marijuana 
the american academy of ophthalmology committee on drugs says 
that while marijuana can lower intraocular pressure there is no 
evidence the drug can safely and effectively lower it enough to 
prevent optic nerve damage 
besides the longterm lung damage that can occur from smoking 
the drug shortterm side effects include euphoria low blood 
pressure and eye dryness the committee said the panel said 
longterm studies are needed 
dr keith green a regents professor of ophthalmology at the 
medical college of georgia in augusta ga who has studied 
marijuana said better drugs than marijuana are available for 
glaucoma patients 
if this were a worthwhile venture there would be much greater 
utilization and recommendation of its use by the physicians in the 
ophthalmology community green said 
but dr ivan silverberg a medical oncologist in san francisco 
said that among cancer and aids patients theres still a lot of 
interest in using marijuana to control nausea and pain 
patients use it all the time he said its very common in 
the bay area among older as well as younger patients 
he added that while this is not the greatest drug known to 
man it is the most effective of the outpatient drugs for 
controlling nausea because patients can get relief in a matter of 
seconds without having to swallow a pill and keep it down for 30 to 
90 minutes also smoking allows a patient better dose control 
because they can stop when they get relief he said 
silverberg said hes not willing to go through the steps needed 
to get permission to prescribe marijuana for patients because the 
governments process is too timeconsuming and patients who want it 
can easily get it 
i dont prescribe it i dont smoke it and i dont have a 
reputation as a pot doctor silverberg said but he added if 
i think a patient is going to be nauseated well talk about it 
</TEXT>
