seoul south korea ap president roh taewoo has agreed to 
dissolve his governing party to create a new conservative party in 
alliance with two moderate opposition groups top politicians said 
sunday 
roh also has agreed to revise the constitution to replace the 
countrys present presidential system of government with a 
parliamentary system to be headed by a prime minister the 
officials said 
the plan is designed to break a deadlock in the legislature 
which is controlled by three opposition parties whose strong 
rivalries have prevented them from working together against the 
governing party 
the plan would also dwarf the nations most radical opposition 
party the party for peace and democracy and its charismatic 
leader kim daejung 
in addition the parliamentary system would allow roh the chance 
to remain in power as prime minister after his fiveyear term as 
president ends in 1993 
those familiar with the agreement said it will be formalized at 
a meeting monday between roh kim youngsam leader of the no 2 
opposition group the reunification democratic party and kim 
jongpil a former premier who heads the no 3 opposition group 
the new democratic republican party 
kim jongpil said the threeway talks will formally announce the 
creation of a new conservative party everything has been set for 
the new party he told a meeting of party lawmakers sunday night 
he said five delegates from each party will begin working 
together tuesday to prepare for the new party expected to emerge 
about a month later 
an official in the governing democratic justice party said that 
the three parties agreed during weeks of private discussions to 
create a new party and to change the constitution to adopt a 
cabinet system of government 
they also agreed that the new party to be formed will try to 
comprise all liberal democratic forces said the official who 
requested anonymity 
insiders said roh agreed to the realignment initiated by the 
two opposition parties after kim youngsam reversed himself and 
agreed to support changing from a presidential system to a cabinet 
system of government 
the new party could be a serious setback for kim daejung 
leader of the hardline opposition party for peace and democracy 
his party would be dwarfed by the new party thus limiting his 
chances of coming to power 
the governing party may have agreed to the realignment because 
it has no clear successor to roh whose single fiveryear term 
expires in 1993 
governing party officials have made it clear they hope to 
imitate japans governing liberal democratic party which has long 
remained in power under a cabinet system of government 
rohs governing party has been in an uncomfortable situation 
since it lost a parliamentary majority in the 1988 general 
elections the three main opposition parties have a combined 
majority in the 299member national assembly but intense rivalry 
has made it difficult for them to cooperate 
the new party to be formed is expected to have a collective 
leadership with roh serving as a ceremonial head 
a merger of the three parties will also assure it of a twothird 
majority required in parliament to introduce the constitutional 
revision 
insiders said the new party would push a constitutional revision 
during the term of the current assembly which expires in may 
1992 a constitutional draft adopted in parliament must be approved 
in a national referendum 
even if a new constitution is adopted rohs term which expires 
in february 1993 is expected to be completed by him 
