<TEXT>
congress is bracing for partisan budget fights 
over defense spending the social security system and tax breaks as 
president bush prepares to unveil his proposed 1991 fiscal plan at 
months end 
bushs budget which sources say will call for 124 trillion in 
spending is already being panned by democrats who control congress 
for its expected embrace of assorted dogeared republican proposals 
to save money these include eliminations or reductions of domestic 
programs like mass transit aid and energy assistance to the poor 
this will be a dinosaur budget a warmover of what weve seen 
before senate budget committee chairman james sasser dtenn 
said recently it will be the whole laundry list that congress 
hasnt accepted for nine years 
for their part republicans are already showing that they will 
not be bashful about pushing their own budgetary agenda this year 
in a speech last week bush referred to demagogues who are 
opposing his resurrected proposal to cut the tax rate on capital 
gains which he claims will raise money for government coffers 
the higher pitched political rhetoric is being fanned by the 
fact that this is an election year with the entire house and 
onethird of the senate up for reelection in november members of 
the two parties plan to use the budget to show voters what they 
stand for and how they differ from their opponents 
both parties will be jockeying for position foresees house 
budget committee chairman leon panetta dcalif democrats will 
be pushing for increased initiatives on human needs and 
republicans will be trying to protect their no new taxes pledge 
frankly both positions together arent going to help speed the 
budget process 
the budget year that bush launches when he submits his spending 
blueprint to congress on jan 29 is expected to be have three major 
battlefields each contest will shape a crucial part of the savings 
mix the president needs to heed the grammrudman laws requirement 
for a projected deficit next year of no more than 64 billion 
bowing to deficit pressures and to diminishing tensions with the 
eastern bloc bush plans to call for 303 billion in defense 
spending which would be 2 percent less than necessary to keep this 
years 297 billion level abreast of inflation 
democrats with liberals such as reps george miller dcalif 
and barney frank dmass leading the way are already saying 
bushs cut is not deep enough even the more moderate sasser says 
he would like to see military spending reduced to about 295 
billion 
with democrats holding majorities in the house and senate the 
only questions seem to be how large the socalled peace 
dividend will be and where the savings will go the majority 
party is split over the latter with liberals urging an expansion 
of ailing domestic programs like education and health and others 
hoping to use the savings to lower the deficit 
another fight will be over the huge surpluses the social 
security system is running 
there is bipartisan consensus that the surplus does little more 
than hide the true size of the overall deficit which was 152 
billion last year but would have been 204 billion without the 
social security windfall the dispute arises over what to do about 
it 
although opinions on the issue cross party lines republicans 
tend to couple removal of the social security surpluses from 
deficit calculations with an extension of the grammrudman law 
that legislation which mandates a balanced budget in 1993 and then 
expires tends to keep domestic spending down most democrats 
oppose a grammrudman extension 
a wild card is a proposal by sen daniel moynihan dny who 
wants to lower the 765 percent payroll tax employers and workers 
pay to support social security the plan puts bush in the 
uncomfortable position of opposing a tax cut but opponents say the 
reduction would jeopardize the savings needed to pay baby boomers 
retirement benefits 
house speaker thomas s foley dwash in his first public 
statement on the plan said sunday he would vote against the plan 
if he had to vote on it now he called for the proposal to be 
studied very carefully 
also likely to cause a clash is bushs capital gains reduction 
plan democrats who say the proposal is actually a moneyloser 
narrowly defeated it in 1989 after a bitter political clash but 
concede that the measure will likely be enacted this year 
a fight will evolve as democrats struggle to win something in 
return perhaps an improved individual retirement account to 
benefit the middle and lowerclass 
other elements of the years budget clash should sound familiar 
chief among them will be questions over the administrations 
economic projections the better the economic forecast the more 
revenues the government can expect to collect and the lower the 
anticipated deficit 
administration sources say they will project next years 
economic growth to be about 26 percent well above the amount many 
private economists expect since the grammrudman law requires use 
of the administration forecast democrats are helpless to do more 
than complain 
using these optimistic projections the white house is expected 
to say that it needs 30 billion to 35 billion in savings to reach 
the grammrudman deficit target of 64 billion the nonpartisan 
congressional budget office is expected to say that the needed 
savings will be more than twice as high 
bush is expected to propose minor initiatives in certain 
education environment antidrug child care and science programs 
democrats are ready to claim that his proposals fall short of what 
is needed 
</TEXT>
