<TEXT>
vermonts gubernatorial election is 
months away but analysts are already excited about the possibility 
of a threeway race involving three nationally recognized 
politicians 
bernard sanders burlingtons former socialist mayor and former 
republican gov richard snelling are both leaning toward 1990 
gubernatorial bids the democratic incumbent madeleine kunin is 
expected to seek reelection 
it would be the super bowl of vermont politics said john 
franco the burlington city attorney and a close associate of 
sanders 
it would be the wildest gubernatorial race said sen 
douglas racine the senate president pro tem 
snelling is expected to announce his intentions this week 
sanders is planning to reveal his plans within two weeks kunin is 
not expected to make any announcement until after the current 
legislative session ends sometime this spring 
all three politicians have achieved national prominence over the 
past decade kunin the states first woman governor has taken 
strong stands on the environment and abortion rights sanders is 
well known for his eight years as the socialist mayor of vermonts 
largest city and snelling a republican is a former chairman of 
the national governors association 
in vermont a candidate for governor must win a majority if no 
candidate does the election is decided not by a runoff but in the 
legislature this is precisely what happened in 1986 when sanders 
last made a try for governor kunin received 47 percent of the 
votes the republican peter smith got 38 percnet and sanders got 
14 percent the democratcontrolled legislature gave the nod to 
kunin 
at present democrats maintain a narrow edge in the legislature 
kunin now in her third twoyear term has seen her support slip 
in recent months as the states economy has slowed prompting her 
to call for budget cuts and tax increases some also oppose her 
calls for such measures as a ban on disposable diapers 
snelling who served as governor from 1977 to 1985 has been 
urged to run by republicans who feel he is the gops best chance of 
winning back the office the former governor said he will run if 
i find that i can contribute to solving the problems that are out 
there 
sanders who stepped down as mayor last year considers himself 
a socialist but runs as an independent he gained new credibility 
when he ran a strong second ahead of the democratic candidate 
former house majority leader paul poirier in the 1988 race for the 
us house 
poirier said sanders shouldnt be underestimated adding 
bernie made a believer out of me 
franco said you can safely say bernard sanders will be a 
statewide candidate in 1990 but added i can tell you he has 
not made up his mind about running for congress or governor 
sanders was out of town late last week and could not be reached 
for comment 
kunin supporters say that a challenge from snelling alone would 
not force the governor out of a race madeleine kunin doesnt 
walk away from fights said her former press spokesman robert 
sherman 
but the entry of both snelling and sanders would dramatically 
alter the political reality it would be a very tough race for 
her poirier said all three of them would start out as 
equals 
a snellingsanderskunin race starts out with the advantage 
going to the republican said peter welch a democrat and a 
former state senate leader who said sanders and kunin would split 
the progressive vote 
elizabeth bankowski kunins former chief of staff disagreed 
dont ever underestimate madeleine kunins ability to rise to 
the occasion she said 
snelling who might face a republican primary challenge from 
michael bernhardt would be the first former vermont governor to 
try to regain the office since erastus fairbanks did so in 1860 
his greatest task would be to persuade voters he has a vision for 
the state in the 1990s 
bankowski revealed kunins slant on a snelling candidacy i 
dont think thats what the governor meant when she called on 
vermonters to do more recycling 
