<TEXT>
a study by university deans released sunday 
predicts an intense tugofwar among government industry and 
academia for people with doctorate degrees 
as a result the association of american universities said the 
nations competitive stature can only weaken in comparison 
with other industrialized countries 
this nation faces a serious shortage of phds said the 
report a sharply increased demand will outstrip phd production 
before the turn of the century industry government and 
universities will be pitted against each other in a battle for 
critical human capital 
the report the phd shortage the federal role was 
prepared by a ninemember working group of primarily graduate deans 
from aau institutions it said the nation will suffer an annual 
shortage of 7500 natural science and engineering doctorates just a 
few years into the next century shortages of doctorate degrees in 
the humanities and social sciences will occur even sooner said the 
report 
faculty shortages already have appeared in engineering 
business and other highdemand fields the report said 
in 1985 an estimated 43 percent of all doctorates employed in 
the united states were working outside of higher education seventy 
percent of 1987 engineering doctorates had commitments in 
nonacademic sectors 53 percent in industry and 17 percent in 
government and other nonacademic sectors about 65 percent of 1987 
doctorate recipients in the physical sciences had employment 
commitments in nonacademic sectors 50 percent in industry 15 
percent in other nonacademic sectors 
across all fields 50 percent of 1987 doctorate recipients had 
employment outside academia said the report 
the report follows a study in september 1989 by the mellon 
foundation that estimated there will be only eight applicants for 
every 10 liberal arts faculty jobs by the year 2000 
it also comes on the heel of a call to higher education 
institutions last friday by education secretary lauro cavazos to 
increase by 25 percent the number of us college graduates 
completing doctoral programs in the basic arts mathematics 
sciences engineering and technological disciplines 
the current shortages have been somewhat masked by the heavy 
enrollment of foreign students in phd programs in science and 
engineering and by the desire of those students to spend at least 
some postdoctoral years in employment in this country said aau 
president robert rosenzweig 
we should be grateful for that fact but as many observers 
have noted it is a foolishly risky assumption for the future 
rosenzweig said the government has an essential role in 
assuring that the nations intellectual life and economic vitality 
remain healthily fed by successvie generations of talent trained to 
the highest levels of which our universities are capable 
the report recommended a significant expansion of federal 
support for graduate education and a doubling of federal 
fellowships and traineeships 
the aau is an organization of 56 major us research 
universities 
