<TEXT>
prime minister vp singh said sunday his 
government will scrap the 470 million settlement reached with 
union carbide over the bhopal gas leak and will pursue criminal 
charges and the 3 billion originally sought 
we believe there can be no deal over human corpses singh 
told survivors of the 1984 disaster which killed more than 3500 
people 
the settlement was accepted last year by the indian supreme 
court and by singhs predecessor rajiv gandhi 
singh was greeted by surging crowds when he arrived at the 
jaiprakash nagar shantytown where many of the victims of the gas 
leak lived 
some people draped garlands of flowers around singhs neck or 
knelt to touch his feet as he walked through the narrow lanes of 
huts just across the street from the nowclosed union carbide plant 
at a public rally attended by an estimated 100000 people 
onetenth of bhopals population singh declared we have decided 
to do away with the settlement and pursue the 3 billion suit 
against the company and also the criminal suit against ucc union 
carbide corp officials 
he promised that his government would provide interim relief to 
all people living in gasaffected areas the amount of money to be 
paid will be determined within one month he said 
we must look at the bhopal gas tragedy as a national disaster 
and involve all organizations to provide succor to the survivors 
said singh who took office dec 2 
the prime minister did not spell out how his government would 
revive the legal case in the worlds deadliest industrial disaster 
the supreme court the highest in the nation on feb 15 
accepted a 470 million deal as full and final settlement of 
the governments suit which had been dragging through a maze of 
indian court procedures for about four years 
the gandhi government originally sought 3 billion in damages 
and later filed criminal negligence charges against top officials 
of the connecticutbased union carbide corp and its local 
subsidiary union carbide of india ltd 
when union carbide and the gandhi government agreed on the 470 
million the indian supreme court absolved the company of further 
civil or criminal liability 
however under indian law the decision is subject to review if 
challenged gas victims and activist groups filed petitions with 
the court challenging the settlement on two grounds that the 
gandhi government had no right to declare itself the sole 
representative of all claims arising from the bhopal gas disaster 
and that the compensation of 470 million was inadequate 
the supreme court declared dec 22 that the gandhi government 
did indeed have the right to be the claimants only 
representative 
the second challenge is still pending and the singh government 
announced jan 12 it would support the challengers 
union carbide has maintained the gas leak was the result of 
sabotage by a disgruntled employee at the bhopal plant the 
government maintained the disaster was caused by company negligence 
methyl isocyanate a liquid used in making pesticides leaked 
from a tank and turned into a deadly vapor when it hit the air dec 
3 1984 when most people were asleep 
many people died in their sleep or as they tried to flee in the 
choking white cloud 
according to figures compiled by the government of madhya 
pradesh state which includes bhopal the death toll has reached 
3598 about half the victims died immediately or within a few days 
of exposure to the gas the others died later of respiratory and 
other problems caused by the gas according to government records 
an additional 20000 people are still classified as injured 
