<TEXT>
east germany averted a major 
nuclear power accident in 1976 that could have been as devasting as 
the one at chernobyl in the soviet union a west german magazine 
said sunday 
east german officials have not disclosed the potential 
seriousness of the incident der spiegel said 
the hamburgbased magazine said the incident took place in 1976 
at the sovietdesigned nuclear power plant called lubmin near the 
town of greifswald in northern east germany 
quoting a former engineer from the plant spiegel said careless 
manipulation of an electrical grounding system by one of the 
plants electricians resulted in a major fire that destroyed most 
of the cable network 
the fire disabled six cooling pumps for the block i reactor at 
the plant and five of six backup pumps were also inactivated 
spiegel said 
it was only through luck that one of the backup pumps 
functioned spiegel said explaining that the backup pump had been 
accidentally hooked up to the electrical system of block ii which 
was functioning 
if the one backup pump had not functioned a meltdown as 
devastating as the 1986 chernobyl accident could have occurred and 
would have spread radioactive fallout over much of northern 
germany sweden and denmark the magazine said 
spiegel quoting the engineer said that the east german army 
was called in to clean up the plant which was repaired and put 
back into operation four months later it did not identify the 
engineer 
the report which is to appear in the weekly magazines monday 
edition was provided in advance to other news media 
the april 26 1986 explosion at the no 4 reactor of the 
fourunit chernobyl nuclear power plant was the worlds worst 
atomic accident two workers died immediately of burns they 
suffered in the explosion 28 died shortly after the accident from 
radiation exposure and one died of a heart attack while fighting 
the fire 
the accident sent a cloud of radiation over large parts of 
northern and central europe leading to bans on foodstuffs from 
several countries 
