blacks and whites as to how police and mayor raymond l flynn 
handled the oct 23 killing whether they consider boston safe and 
whether they advocate a police stopandsearch policy 
nine of 10 black residents surveyed said they believe the city 
police department overreacted in its investigation of the stuart 
case while white residents responded by a 54 ratio that the 
police response was warranted 
flynn whom many black leaders have blamed for encouraging a 
blanket search of the mission hill neighborhood following the 
murder still retained support with a 68percentto20 percent 
favorable rating that reflected nearly even support from both 
blacks and whites 
among blacks 32 percent said they would be less likely to vote 
for flynn for governor because of the stuart case while 47 percent 
said it would have no impact among whites 19 percent said the 
case would have a negative effect while 68 percent said it would 
have no impact 
flynn is considered a potential candidate for governor this fall 
experts said the survey which had a margin of error of plus or 
minus 5 percent clearly indicated that the citys black and white 
communities had dissimilar views of the stuart case 
in question after question there is a clear and significant 
difference of opinion between blacks and whites about the case 
said pollster gerry chervinsky of krc communications research 
which handled the poll 
by and large whites believe there was an action that was 
perpetrated by stuart that duped everybody and that flynn the 
district attorney and the police department did what they should 
have done the black community doesnt seem to buy into that 
among other findings in the poll 
seventyfour percent of blacks polled said they believed 
police improperly persuaded witnesses to implicate william bennett 
a black man later cleared in mrs stuarts slaying that compared 
with 42 percent of the whites 
overall 57 percent of the respondents said they believe black 
suspects in crimes are treated more harshly than white suspects 
blacks by a 7to1 ratio said they believe black suspects are 
treated more harshly 
eightyfive percent of blacks questioned compared with 51 
percent of whites do not believe police administer justice equally 
in all boston neighborhoods 
fiftythree percent of blacks questioned compared with 25 
percent of whites said they do not feel personally safe living in 
boston 
fiftyfive percent of blacks and 49 percent of whites said the 
news media had done a belowaverage job of reporting the story 
although flynn retained a high favorability rating he and his 
colleagues district attorney newman flanagan and police 
commissioner mickey roache scored badly in their handling of the 
stuart case with the trios performance rated belowaverage by 
about 54 percent of blacks and 32 percent of whites 
